{"cursor":"3932","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In physics, the 'Gell-MannâOkubo mass formula' provides a sum rule for baryon\nand meson masses within a specific multiplet determined by isospin and\nhypercharge (or equivalently strangeness). The rule was first formulated by\nMurray Gell-Mann in 1961. {{cite paper |author=M. Gell-Mann |year=1961\n|title=The Eightfold Way: A Theory of Strong Interaction Symmetry\n|publisher=California Institute of Technology |series=Synchrotron Laboratory\nReport CTSL-20 |doi=10.2172/4008239 |osti=4008239 }} and independently\nproposed by Susumu Okubo in 1962 {{cite journal |author=S. Okubo |year=1962\n|title=Note on Unitary Symmetry in Strong Interactions |journal=Progress of\nTheoretical Physics |volume=27 |issue=5 |pages=949â966\n|bibcode=1962PThPh..27..949O |doi=10.1143/PTP.27.949 }} {{cite\njournal |author=S. Okubo |year=1962 |title=Note on Unitary Symmetry in Strong\nInteractions. II âExcited States of Baryonsâ |journal=Progress of Theoretical\nPhysics |volume=28 |issue=1 |pages=24â32 |bibcode=1962PThPh..28...24O\n|doi=10.1143/PTP.28.24 }} Isospin and hypercharge are in their simplest\ngeneralization generated by SU(3), which can be represented by eight unitary and\ntraceless matrices corresponding to the \"components\" of isospin and hypercharge.\nSix of the matrices correspond to flavor change, and the final two correspond to\nthe third-component of isospin projection, and hypercharge.\n\nFor the baryon octet, the final matrix for hypercharge can be transformed to\nprovide two mass difference matrices relating the masses of the baryons within\nthe octet. Using these matrices the Gell-MannâOkubo formula can be written for\nthe baryon octet,\n\n: 2(m_N+m_\\Xi) = 3m_\\Lambda + m_\\Sigma \\, \n\nwhere m N is the average mass of the proton and neutron,\nm Ξ the average mass of the Ξ 0 and\nΞ − , and m Σ the average mass of\nΣ 0, Σ +, and Σ − .\n\nThe same mass relation can be found for the meson octet, but now the masses are\nsquared. {{cite book |author=D. J. Griffiths |year=1987\n|title=Introduction to Elementary Particles |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=0-471-60386-\n4 }}\n\n: \\frac{1}{2}\\left((m_{K^-}+m_{\\bar{K}^0})^2 + (m_{K^+}+m_{K^0})^2\\right) =\n:3m_\\eta^2 + \\frac{1}{9}(m_{\\pi^0}+m_{\\pi^+}+m_{\\pi^-})^2\n\nFor the baryon decuplet, the mass formula is given by three relations,\n\n: m_\\Delta-m_{\\Sigma^*} = m_{\\Sigma^*}-m_{\\Xi^*} = m_{\\Xi^*}-m_\\Omega\n:\\, \n\nwhere m X is the average mass between the neutral and charged\ninstances of particle X, just as is done in the baryon octet formulation.\nThe baryon decuplet formula allowed Gell-Mann to successfully predict the mass\nof the yet undiscovered Ω − .\n","linknr":120,"url":"Gell-Mann–Okubo_mass_formula","recorded":1374783962,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Gell-Mann%E2%80%93Okubo_mass_formula&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Gell-Mann%E2%80%93Okubo_mass_formula&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Physics","/wiki/Baryon","/wiki/Meson","/wiki/Isospin","/wiki/Hypercharge","/wiki/Strangeness","/wiki/Murray_Gell-Mann","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Susumu_Okubo","#cite_note-2","#cite_note-3","/wiki/SU(3)","/wiki/Gell-Mann_matrice